archimate:ArchimateDiagramModel.name: Service MetaModel
archimate:ArchimateDiagramModel.documentation: This view of the DWP Architecture Framework shows the detail of the significant elements for describing the service architecture.

children.content: A Journey Element may need to consume Information to perform and may provide information as a result of its operation, these are documented in the Information Chain / Risk Profile associated with the journey.

A Journey and Journey Element has a risk profile, built initially from the information flow through the service. As time goes on the service takes shape and more vulnerabilities and attack vectors can be identified.

A Journey is a behavioural element that can be associated with a Customer / Consumer of a service, with the actions of the service as a whole and with the contributions of individual services and a specialised version allows an information journey / risk profile to be built

The value proposition is the collection of values the business expects to be delivered by this customer facing service and will have both the expected context and intended scope of the service under consideration.

Each requirement placed on the service, journey and journey element that emerge through discovery will (probably) have an expected value that contributes towards the intended values / standing targets.

Each element of a journey has some motivation behind it. Why does this happen, what is its intent, why is it needed. Some of the patterns emerge because we are doing things for similar reasons, the core of these patterns may form a re-use pattern.

The customer journey is used to represent many different types of customer, the most obvious of which are the benefit claimant and internal agents that participate directly in aspects of the service provision. However valid customer journeys should include those more intagible journeys that cover the tasks involved in the management, support

Each type of service may have some basic associated patterns. Domain services are of special interest, they are centred around the information and emerge because we are gathering and manipulating information considered useful to the organisation, these are intrinsically re-usable. There are two main foci of Domain Services, Business Domain Data and Business Critical Data, both are Domain Driven the former to do with the context in which the data is used the latter to do with data critical to the success of the business that cuts across many different Business Domains.
This view of the DWP Architecture Framework shows the detail of the significant elements for describing the service architecture.
An assumption may be connected to any element. It is used to document assumptions that have been made.
